               <p>1957. <persName id="def1-1957-18430612" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1957-18430612" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1957-18430612" type="surname" value="BRIDGEWATER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1957-18430612" type="given" value="FREDERICK LUTMAN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">FREDERICK LUTMAN BRIDGEWATER</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430612-1957-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430612-1957-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430612-1957-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18430612-cd-216" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430612-1957-offence-1 t18430612-cd-216"></join>30th of May</rs>, 1 coat, value 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 1 ring, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 8 yards of velvet, 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18430612-name-1369" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1369" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1369" type="surname" value="PRICE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1369" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430612-1957-offence-1 t18430612-name-1369"></join>John Price</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1370" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1370" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1370" type="surname" value="PRICE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1370" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN PRICE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Great North-street, Lisson-grove, and am a grocer. The prisoner lived with me—on Tuesday, the 30th of May, I was out, and returned at three o'clock in the afternoon—I had not seen the prisoner when I went, nor when I came back—he is my son-in-law, and his mother, who was my wife, was then on her death-bed—on my return home she gave me some account, and on the Friday afterwards she died—after her death I looked in a drawer, and missed a coat—on the Saturday the prisoner came to my house—I said he had taken the coat—he said, "Oh, it is very easy to get that back again, that was pawned for 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>."—he gave me the duplicate, and said he had got two others—I said, "You have not taken anything else, have you?"—he said, "Yes, a piece of velvet and a ring"—I said, "You are a bad young man, I shall never forgive you"—he brought me the tickets on Sunday morn<lb></lb>ing, and left them on the mantel-piece—I redeemed the coat—I have not redeemed the other things.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was not his answer that he had not pawned the coat for much? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He said so—I am not in business now, I am in a private lodging—I dined with the prisoner on the Monday, in Moorgate-street, with a friend—it was on Sunday he brought the duplicates—I told him I should prosecute him—about seven o'clock on the Tuesday morning he came drunk in a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>, and knocked at my door—the <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>-man gave him in charge for not paying his fare—the prisoner has had some money left him lately—Mr. Shadwell, of Gray's Inn, is one of the executors, and he is the person to pay that money—I did not send a person to Mr. Shadwell to get 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., which was part of the money owing to the prisoner—I know 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. has been paid on ac<lb></lb>count—I did not send a person to Mr. Shadwell with the prisoner's consent to get 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. of that money—I mean to swear I did not receive 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I never received a farthing—I had 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from the prisoner's friend—I know nothing about its being a portion of the 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I thought he lent me the money—I be<lb></lb>lieve I owe the man the 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—the 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. came from the 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—the prisoner had 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., that was all he had of the 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—there is a balance due to him from Mr. Shadwell, I know—I have been to see the prisoner since he has been commit<lb></lb>ted—I saw him on the Saturday—I did not want him to send me to Mr. Shadwell for the rest of the money—the prisoner wrote me a letter that he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184306120193"></xptr>
               <p>wanted to see me—I do not know when my coat was pawned—I had to pay a halfpenny interest for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Upon your oath, if you had received an assignment from the prisoner of the money due to him, should you have prosecuted this case? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, just the same—I told him I should prosecute him—I did not give him in charge before the Tuesday, because I was waiting till after the mother's funeral—she was not buried till the Sunday week; but it was on the Sunday after her death I had the conversation with the prisoner—I did not give him in custody on that Sunday, because I was in so much trouble—I will swear I had not been asking him to execute an assignment of that property—I dined with him and his friend in Moorgate-street on the Monday—his friend had received a cheque for 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from Mr. Shad well—I do not know whether the dinner was paid for out of that money—the prisoner had 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. of it—it was an understanding with his friend that he would procure him a situation for 25<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I do not know that the prisoner preferred trusting that friend to me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1371" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1371" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1371" type="surname" value="BALL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1371" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES BALL</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with Mr. Trail, a pawnbroker. I produce a gold ring, pawned by the prisoner on the 30th of May, for 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., in the name of James Lawrence—I produce some cotton velvet which was not pawned by the prisoner—I gave this duplicate for it.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">Property produced and sworn to</hi>)</p>
